Analyse Population¶

The population in africa will increase dramatically in the coming years and the population needs energy to meet the needs. As you can see from the difference between urban and rural, more and more people are moving into the city and this is causing greater energy consumption. From 2060 onwards, urban development will continue to increase and rural development will decrease sharply. This population growth will pose a problem in Africa and for us in Europe.

Analyse Capacity Electricity¶

As the graph shows us very clearly, in each scenario the capacity utilisation is high. In a "no policy" scenario, the desired maximum utilisation would not be achieved, which would be a pity if we think about how the population will develop in the next few years and where each GW plays a role.

Agricultural Production:¶

Analyse Solar¶

The potential for solar energy and analagen is enormous in Africa, like no other continent. When you look at the best-case scenario of production increasing a thousandfold within 80 years, an investment in this area would be an enormous gain for the supply in Africa and the environment.

The costs would be high at the beginning but they would fall in the coming decades, considering that by the end of this century the costs will have fallen by more than 80%. It is an expensive investment at the moment, but it will pay off in the future.

Analyse Wind¶

Wind is not as effective as solar but the capacity is still there (up to 2000 GW at the end of 2100 in the best scenario and over 1000GW in the worst).

In the case of offshore plants, you can see that the investment only rises in 2055 and falls dramatically in 2055, I can't explain how this data comes about. Since I don't know how windy the coastal regions of the African continent are, I can't judge.

The situation is very different for onshore ana lyses. They have a long lifespan and capacity will increase rapidly from 2060 onwards.
